          <h2>The Architect Of Modern India</h2>
          <p>
            Jawaharlal Nehru, often hailed as the "Architect of Modern India,"
            played a pivotal role in shaping the nation's destiny after
            independence. His vision and leadership were instrumental in laying
            the foundations for a secular, democratic, and socialist republic.
            Nehru's policies focused on industrialization, education, and social
            reforms, aiming to build a modern India that could compete on the
            global stage. His legacy is evident in the nation's democratic
            institutions, scientific advancements, and cultural diversity.
          </p>
          <h3>Early Life and Education</h3>
          <p>
            Birth and childhood in Allahabad Education at Harrow School and
            Trinity College, Cambridge Involvement in Indian nationalism during
            his student days
          </p>

          <h3>Political Career</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Return to India and involvement in the Indian National Congress
            </li>
            <li>
              Participation in the Non-Cooperation Movement and Civil
              Disobedience Movement
            </li>
            <li>Imprisonment for his political activities</li>
            <li>Role in the Indian independence movement</li>
            <li>
              Leadership of the Indian National Congress after Gandhi's
              assassination
            </li>
            <li>First Prime Minister of independent India</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Vision for Modern India</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Secularism and religious tolerance</li>
            <li>Democracy and democratic</li>
            <li>institutions Social justice and equality</li>
            <li>Economic development and industrialization</li>
            <li>Foreign policy and non-alignment</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Achievements,Challenges and Controversies</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>-Drafting and implementation of the Indian Constitution</li>
            <li>-Establishment of a secular and democratic republic</li>
            <li>-Industrialization and economic development</li>
            <li>-Promotion of education and scientific research</li>
            <li>-Kashmir issue</li>
            <li>-Sino-Indian War</li>
            <li>-Indo-Pakistani Wars</li>
            <li>-Economic challenges and planning</li>
            <li>-Personal criticisms and controversies</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>Legacy</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Architect of modern India</li>
            <li>Champion of democracy, secularism, and social justice</li>
            <li>Promoter of education, science, and culture</li>
            <li>
              Influence on Indian foreign policy and international relations
            </li>
            <li>Continued relevance and impact on India's development</li>
          </ul>
          <h3>
            "Every country has a right to choose its own way of life and to
            build its own society."
          </h3>
